# documentation-standards

## principles

- honest, direct, factual; acknowledge limits
- no marketing/superlatives/buzzwords
- human-centered where relevant; concrete examples
- technically accurate; verify claims; precise terms

## structure

- start with overview and purpose
- middle: implementation details and usage
- end: examples and troubleshooting
- use bullets for lists
- use code blocks for examples

## language and tone

- professional, precise, approachable
- active voice; concise
- document what exists (not future plans)
- avoid subjective descriptors; use measurable terms

## README requirements

- Clear project title and description
- Installation/setup instructions
- Usage examples
- Prerequisites and dependencies
- How to run tests
- Project structure overview
- Contributing guidelines (if applicable)
- License information

## checklist

- no marketing or unverified claims
- logical flow, consistent terms
- technical accuracy verified
- audience-appropriate depth
- includes examples where helpful
- installation steps are clear and complete
- all dependencies documented

## Table of Contents

- Always use `<!-- omit from toc -->` for headings that should be excluded from the table of contents.
- Never manually update table of content entries, as they are automatically generated by plugins.
- Always ensure that generated table of contents accurately reflect the document structure.
